BUNCH ROT, GRAPEVINE - ITALY: (SICILY) NEW STRAINS
**************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 3 Sep 2015
Source: FreshPlaza [edited]
http://www.freshplaza.com/article/145249/Sicily-gray-mould-may-have-become-fungicides-resistant


Gray mould, caused by _Botrytis cinerea_, is among the most serious fungal disease of table grape (_Vitis vinifera_) worldwide. This pathogen is responsible for heavy losses in Mazzarrone, among the most important Italian areas for table grape production.

From 2009 to 2013, scientists collected 302 single-spore isolates of _B. cinerea_ from vineyards in [the] district [and] evaluated in vitro sensitivity to [6 fungicides from different chemical classes], identified point mutations in field isolates resistant to different fungicides, and investigated the presence of isolates with multiple fungicide resistance.

45.7 per cent were found to be resistant to at least 1 fungicide. About 10 per cent had multiple resistance to at least 2 or more individual fungicides. [Some] isolates [showed] simultaneous resistance to 4 different classes of fungicides. Accordingly, these fungicides failed to control infections by isolates with resistance or reduced sensitivity.

This study represents the 1st report of _B. cinerea_ field isolates with single or multiple resistance to botryticides. By continuous selection of multi-resistant isolates, chemical control of gray mould in vineyards will become increasingly difficult. Thus, careful monitoring of sensitivity and multiple resistance to botryticides over time will be crucial in managing fungicide resistance. [Fungicides] should be [used] in alternation or in mixtures with different [modes of] action and low risk of resistance development.

[Ref: A Panebianco et al (2015): Detection of _Botrytis cinerea_ field isolates with multiple fungicide resistance from table grape in Sicily. Crop Protection 77, 65-73; DOI: 10.1016/j.cropro.2015.07.010;
http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S026121941530065X
Table of fungicides used in the study:
http://www.freshplaza.com/2015/0902/Grapes_table.png]

[Byline: Emanuela Fontana]

