Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org

[The fungus _Botrytis cinerea_ can cause serious losses in both yield and fruit quality of grapevine. It causes lesions on leaves and also infects shoots, flowers, and fruit, leading to bunch rot. If blossoms are infected, the fungus remains latent until berries begin to soften. Infection is optimal at 15-20 deg C with free water or over 90 per cent humidity.

Grape cultivars with dense canopies, thin skins, and/or tight clusters are more susceptible. The rot may progress to infect berry clusters or whole bunches, and girdling lesions on the stems may lead to drying and premature fruit drop. Affected berries may split open, develop a grayish mould on the surface, and may shrivel in dry conditions.

The pathogen overwinters on plant material and is spread by water, wind, mechanical means and juice from split berries. Mechanical damage caused by birds or insects creates entry points for the fungus and can greatly increase losses. Disease management relies mainly on fungicide applications, phytosanitation, and cultural practices.

_B. cinerea_ also causes blights and grey molds on a wide range of hosts, including many crops such as brassicas and other vegetables, fruit crops and peanut.

